<h2>Action Button</h2>
<p>
    Behavioral implementation of the <a href="/intents/action/">Action Intent</a>, handling visual priority rendering,
    busy state layout (width locking, visibility), and platform-aware group ordering.
    Works with <a href="/blocks/resource-action/">Resource Action</a> for mutation lifecycle integration.
</p>
<p>
    Action Button is a <strong>behavior layer</strong>, not a visual component. It reads the Action Intent from the
    injector chain and applies the appropriate busy state, icon rendering, and group ordering to the target element.
    Styling is left to CSS &mdash; the block manages attributes and layout constraints.
</p>

<h3>Web Standards Alignment</h3>
<table>
    <tr><th>Standard</th><th>Status</th><th>How We Adopt It</th></tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Invoker_Commands_API">Invoker Commands API</a></td>
        <td>Baseline 2026</td>
        <td>Action buttons can use <code>commandfor</code>/<code>command</code> for declarative mutation invocation</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Accessibility/ARIA/Attributes/aria-disabled">aria-disabled</a></td>
        <td>Standard</td>
        <td><code>withBusyDisabled</code> applies <code>aria-disabled</code> instead of HTML <code>disabled</code>, preserving tab order and screen reader announcements</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Accessibility/ARIA/Attributes/aria-live">aria-live</a></td>
        <td>Standard</td>
        <td>Busy state changes announced via <code>aria-live="polite"</code> on the button's label region</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/contain">CSS Containment</a></td>
        <td>Baseline</td>
        <td>Action groups use <code>contain: layout</code> to prevent busy-state width changes from triggering ancestor reflow</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<h3>Framework Research</h3>
<table>
    <tr><th>Framework</th><th>Key Patterns Adopted</th></tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://mui.com/material-ui/react-button/">Material UI</a></td>
        <td><code>loading</code> prop with spinner replacement; <code>startIcon</code>/<code>endIcon</code> positioning; size variants</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://www.radix-ui.com/primitives/docs/components/button">Radix UI</a></td>
        <td>Composable primitives via <code>asChild</code>; state exposed via <code>data-state</code> attributes for CSS</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://react.fluentui.dev/?path=/docs/components-button--docs">Fluent UI</a></td>
        <td><code>SplitButton</code>, <code>MenuButton</code>, <code>CompoundButton</code> variants for action groups</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://headlessui.com/">Headless UI</a></td>
        <td>Behavior without styling opinions; controlled state; closest to our intent-driven model</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<h3>Busy State Management</h3>
<p>
    When a <a href="/blocks/resource-action/">Resource Action</a> enters <code>pending</code> state,
    Action Button applies busy behavior to the trigger element. Two strategies are available:
</p>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Trait</th><th>Behavior</th><th>CSS Output</th><th>Use Case</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><code>withBusyDisabled</code></td>
            <td>Non-interactive: blocks clicks, shows indicator</td>
            <td><code>aria-disabled="true"</code> + <code>pointer-events: none</code></td>
            <td>Destructive actions (delete, submit payment)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>withBusyInteractive</code></td>
            <td>Reduced feedback: still clickable, visual indicator</td>
            <td><code>opacity: 0.7</code> + spinner overlay</td>
            <td>Non-critical actions (save draft, toggle favorite)</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p>
    <strong>Why <code>aria-disabled</code> over <code>disabled</code>?</strong>
    The HTML <code>disabled</code> attribute removes the element from the tab order and prevents screen readers
    from interacting with it. <code>aria-disabled</code> keeps the element focusable and announced &mdash;
    screen reader users can still discover the button and hear that it's currently busy.
</p>

<h3>Width Lock</h3>
<p>
    The <code>withWidthLock</code> trait prevents layout shift when the button label changes during busy state
    (e.g., "Save" → "Saving..."). Before entering busy state:
</p>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Capture</strong> the element's <code>getComputedStyle().width</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Apply</strong> <code>min-width: {captured}px</code> as an inline style.</li>
    <li><strong>Remove</strong> the inline style when busy state exits.</li>
</ol>
<p>
    This ensures the button never shrinks, preventing reflow of adjacent elements.
    Combined with <code>contain: layout</code> on the parent group, busy state changes are layout-isolated.
</p>

<h3>Platform-Aware Ordering</h3>
<p>
    Confirmation dialogs and action groups have different button ordering conventions per platform.
    <code>withPlatformOrdering</code> reorders child action elements based on OS detection.
</p>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Platform</th><th>Primary Action Position</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>macOS / iOS</strong></td>
            <td>Last (rightmost)</td>
            <td>[Cancel] [Delete]</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Windows / Linux</strong></td>
            <td>First (leftmost)</td>
            <td>[Delete] [Cancel]</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p>
    Detection uses <code>navigator.platform</code> (or <code>navigator.userAgentData.platform</code> where available).
    The ordering can be overridden via injector configuration for cross-platform consistency.
</p>

<h3>Icon Integration</h3>
<p>
    Action Button resolves icon rendering from the <a href="/intents/icon/">Icon Intent</a> provider in the injector chain.
    The button declares <em>what</em> icon it needs (name, size); the Icon Intent decides <em>how</em> to render it
    (SVG sprite, icon font, inline SVG).
</p>
{% highlight "html" %}
<button action-intent="primary"
        action-icon="save"
        action-icon-position="start">
    Save Changes
</button>
{% endhighlight %}

<h3>Usage Examples</h3>

<h4>Basic Action Button with Busy State</h4>
{% highlight "html" %}
<button resource-action="saveUser"
        action-intent="primary"
        action-busy="disabled">
    Save
</button>
<!-- During mutation: aria-disabled="true", min-width locked, label → "Saving..." -->
{% endhighlight %}

<h4>Action Group with Platform Ordering</h4>
{% highlight "html" %}
<div action-group="confirm" action-ordering="platform">
    <button action-intent="secondary" command="cancel">Cancel</button>
    <button action-intent="destructive"
            resource-action="deleteItem"
            resource-action-confirm="Are you sure?"
            action-busy="disabled">
        Delete
    </button>
</div>
<!-- macOS: [Cancel] [Delete]  |  Windows: [Delete] [Cancel] -->
{% endhighlight %}

<h4>Invoker Commands Integration</h4>
{% highlight "html" %}
<button commandfor="user-form"
        command="--save"
        action-intent="primary"
        action-busy="disabled">
    Save
</button>
<form id="user-form" resource-action="saveUser">
    <!-- form fields -->
</form>
{% endhighlight %}

<h3>Styling Hooks</h3>
<p>
    Action Button exposes state via attributes and CSS custom properties, enabling styling without
    JavaScript coupling.
</p>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Selector / Property</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>[aria-disabled="true"]</code></td><td>Button is in busy-disabled state</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>[data-action-busy]</code></td><td>Button is in any busy state (disabled or interactive)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>[data-action-intent="primary|secondary|destructive"]</code></td><td>Visual priority tier</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--action-min-width</code></td><td>Captured width during width lock (set by JS)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--action-opacity</code></td><td>Opacity during busy-interactive state (default: 0.7)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Exports</h3>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Export</th><th>Kind</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>ActionButtonBehavior</code></td><td>Class</td><td>Main behavior (CustomAttribute)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>withBusyDisabled</code></td><td>Trait</td><td>Non-interactive busy state (aria-disabled)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>withBusyInteractive</code></td><td>Trait</td><td>Reduced-feedback busy state (opacity)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>withPlatformOrdering</code></td><td>Trait</td><td>OS-aware action group reordering</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>withWidthLock</code></td><td>Trait</td><td>Layout shift prevention during busy state</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ActionButtonState</code></td><td>Type</td><td>State: idle | busy-disabled | busy-interactive</td></tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
